{"title_page": "List of ambassadors of the United States to Australia", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Infobox Political post\n|post            = Ambassador\n|body            = the United States to Australia\n|nativename      =\n|insignia        = US Department of State official seal.svg\n|insigniasize    = 120\n|insigniacaption = Seal of the United States Department of State\n|image           = Arthur B. Culvahouse, Jr. official photo.jpg\n|alt             = \n|incumbent       = [[Arthur B. Culvahouse Jr.]]\n|incumbentsince  = March 13, 2019\n|nominator       = The [[President of the United States]]\n|appointer           = The [[President of the United States|President]]\n|appointer_qualified = with [[United States Senate|Senate]] [[advice and consent]]\n|inaugural       = [[Clarence E. Gauss]]<br />{{small|(as US Minister to Australia)}}\n|formation       = 1940\n|website         = [https://au.usembassy.gov/ U.S. Embassy - Canberra]\n}}\n\nThe position of '''United States Ambassador to Australia''' has existed since 1940. [[Australia\u2013United States relations|U.S.\u2013Australian relations]] have been close throughout the [[history of Australia]]. Before [[World War II]], [[Australia]] was closely aligned with the [[United Kingdom]], but it has strengthened its relationship with the [[United States]] since 1942, as Britain's influence in Asia has declined and the United States' influence has increased. At the governmental level, United States\u2013Australia relationships are formalised by the [[ANZUS]] treaty and [[Australia-United States Free Trade Agreement]].\n\nThe [[Embassy of the United States, Canberra|embassy]] in [[Canberra]] has always been regarded as a desirable posting and hence has become a patronage position. U.S. Ambassadors to Australia have traditionally been friends, political allies, or former business associates of the President of the day. Some have been major donors to the President's election campaign or political party. Few have been career diplomats ([[Marshall Green]] was a conspicuous exception). The two ambassadors during the [[George W. Bush|Bush]] Administration, for example, were [[Tom Schieffer]], a former business associate of President Bush, and [[Robert McCallum Jr.]], a Bush college friend. The actor [[Fess Parker]] was offered the post in 1985 by [[Ronald Reagan]], after representing Reagan at an event in Australia. Parker considered it, but turned it down.<ref>[http://www.legacy.com/ns/obituary.aspx?pid=140851424 Legacy.com, Fess Parker obituary]</ref>\n\nThis arrangement has suited Australian governments, which welcome the ability of such Ambassadors to gain direct access to the President, bypassing the State Department. The United States was without an ambassador to Australia from September 2016 until February 2019.\n\n==United States Ambassadors to Australia==\nThe following individuals have served as the US Ambassadors to Australia, or any precedent titles:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible\"\n|+ List of US Ambassadors to Australia\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Ordinal\n! scope=\"col\" | Officeholder\n! scope=\"col\" | Image\n! scope=\"col\" | Term began\n! scope=\"col\" | Term ended\n! scope=\"col\" | Time in office\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"; colspan=7 | US Ministers to Australia\n|-\n|align=center| {{nts|1}} || {{sort|Gauss, Clarence E.|[[Clarence E. Gauss]]}} || [[File:Clarence Gauss.png|75px]]  ||align=center| July 17, 1940 ||align=center| March 5, 1941 ||  ||\n|-\n|align=center| {{nts|2}} || {{sort|Johnson, Nelson T.|[[Nelson T. Johnson]]}} || [[File:Nelson T. Johnson cph.3c35451.jpg|75px]] ||align=center| September 12, 1941 ||align=center| April 20, 1945 ||   ||\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"; colspan=7 | US Ambassadors to Australia\n|-\n|align=center| {{nts|3}} || {{sort|Butler, Robert|[[Robert Butler (diplomat)|Robert Butler]]}} ||   ||align=center| 1946 ||align=center| 1948 ||  || <ref>{{cite web |url= https: