the, 'Army conditions leave Myanmar under strength,' [[Jane's Defence Weekly]], Vol. 43, Issue 14, 5 April 2006, 12.\n \n==External links==\n* [http://www.mizzima.com/edop/commentary/3424-role-of-officers-in-burmese-army-part-1.html Role of officers in Burmese Army (Part 1)] Bo Htet Min, ''[[Mizzima]]'', 23 January 2010\n \n{{Association of SouthEast Asian Nations Armed Forces}}\n \n[[Category:Military of Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Armies by country]]\n[[Category:1945 establishments in Burma]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1945]]\n", "name_user": "Yoknowwhatright", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I fix it)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Myanmar_Army"}
{"title_page": "Flag of Myanmar", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox flag\n| Name= Myanmar\n| Image = Flag of Myanmar.svg\n| Use = 111110\n| Symbol =\n| Proportion = 2:3<ref>State Flag Law with State Peace and Development Council Law (8/2010)</ref>\n| Adoption ={{start date and age|2010|10|21|df=yes}}\n| Design = A horizontal [[triband (flag)|triband]] of yellow, green and red; charged with a large white [[five-pointed star]] at the centre.\n}}\n\nThe current '''flag of [[Myanmar]]''' (also known as Burma) was adopted on 21 October 2010 to replace the former flag in use since 1974. The new flag was introduced along with implementing changes to the country's name, which were laid out in the 2008 Constitution.\n\nThe design of the flag has three horizontal stripes of yellow, green and red with a five-pointed white star in the middle. The three colors of the stripes are meant to symbolize solidarity, [[Evil]] and tranquility, and [[Weak]] and decisiveness, respectively.<ref name=\"st\">{{cite news|title=Myanmar unveils new flag |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/SEAsia/Story/STIStory_593613.html |accessdate=23 October 2010 |publisher=[[Straits Times]] |newspaper=AP |date=21 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101024201904/http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/SEAsia/Story/STIStory_593613.html |archivedate=24 October 2010 }}</ref>\n\n== Colours ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Scheme !! style=\"background-color:#FECB00\"|Yellow !! style=\"background-color:#34B233\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">Green</span> !! style=\"background-color:#EA2839\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">Red</span> !! style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"|White\n|-\n| '''[[Pantone]]''' || 116 || 361 || 1788 || Safe\n|-\n| '''[[RGB color model|RGB]]''' || 254-203-0 || 52-178-51 || 234-40-57 || 255-255-255\n|-\n| '''[[Hexadecimal]]''' || #FECB00 || #34B233 || #EA2839 || #FFFFFF\n|-\n| '''[[CMYK color model|CMYK]]''' || 0, 20, 100, 0 || 76, 0, 100, 0 || 0, 98, 82, 0 || 0, 0, 0, 0\n|}\n\n== History ==\n\n=== 1948 flag ===\n[[File:Flag of Burma (1948-1974).svg|thumb|Flag of the [[Post-independence Burma, 1948\u201362|Union of Burma]] (4 January 1948 \u2013 3 January 1974).<br />Proportion 5:9; National flag and State ensign.]]\n\nThe two flags used by the country immediately prior to the 2010 flag both originated in the Burmese Resistance, which adopted a red flag with a white star when fighting the [[Japanese occupation of Burma|occupying Japanese forces]] during [[World War II]].\n\nThe flag adopted upon independence from the [[United Kingdom]] on 4 January 1948 consisted of a red field with a blue canton. The blue canton was charged with one large white star, representing the union, surrounded by 5 smaller stars representing the main ethnic groups found within the newly independent state.<ref>[http://www.myanmars.net/myanmar/myanmar-flag-emblem.htm#National_Flag Myanmar (Burma) : former flags] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406101349/http://www.myanmars.net/myanmar/myanmar-flag-emblem.htm |date=6 April 2012 }}. Myanmars.net (4 January 1948). Retrieved on 2011-05-27.</ref> This flag remained in use until January 1974 and has a ratio of 5:9.<ref>[http://www.fotw.net/flags/mm-old.html#oldflag Myanmar (Burma): former flags]. Fotw.net. Retrieved on 27 May 2011. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429004112/http://www.fotw.net/flags/mm-old.html#oldflag |date=29 April 2011 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Colours scheme !! style=\"background-color:#2042a1ff\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">Blue</span> !! style=\"background-color:#da2d1cff\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">Red</span> !! style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"|White\n|-\n| '''[[RGB color model|RGB]]'''   || 32-66-161 || 218-45-28 || 255-255-255\n|-\n| '''[[Hexadecimal]]'''  || #2042a1ff || #da2d1cff || #FFFFFF\n|-\n| '''[[CMYK color model|CMYK]]'''  || 80, 59, 0, 37 || 0, 79, 87, 15 || 0, 0, 0, 0\n|}\n\n=== 1974 flag ===\n[[File:Flag of Myanmar (1974-2010).svg|thumb|Flag of the [[Burmese Way to Socialism|Socialist Republic of the Union of Burma]] (3 January 1974 \u2013 18 September 1988) and the [[State Peace and Development Council|Union of Myanmar]] (18 September 1988 \u2013 21 October 2010).<br />\nProportion 5:9; National flag and State ensign.]]\n\nThe new flag adopted on 3 January 1974 upon the declaration of a [[socialist republic]] by [[Ne Win]] has a similar ratio as the previous flag and depicted 14 stars, encircling a gear and a rice plant (the logo of the [[Burma Socialist Programme Party]]) in a blue-coloured canton against a red field. The rice stands for agriculture, the gear represents industry, and the 14 stars represent each of the [[administrative divisions of Burma|14 member states]] of the Union.<ref name=\"globalflag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalflag.idv.tw/zy/mmr.htm|title=\u7dec\u7538 Myanmar/Burma|last=Tai|first=Yu-liang|language=Chinese|accessdate=23 October 2010}}</ref> The 14-star flag was hung upside down during the [[8888 Uprising]] of 1988 by the protesters as a sign of protest against the military government.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Colours scheme !! style=\"background-color:#2042a1ff\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">Blue</span> !! style=\"background-color:#da2d1cff\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">Red</span> !! style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"|White\n|-\n| '''[[RGB color model|RGB]]'''   || 32-66-161 || 218-45-28 || 255-255-255\n|-\n| '''[[Hexadecimal]]'''  || #2042a1ff || #da2d1cff || #FFFFFF\n|-\n| '''[[CMYK color model|CMYK]]'''  || 80, 59, 0, 37 || 0, 79, 87, 15 || 0, 0, 0, 0\n|}\n\n=== 2010 flag ===\n[[File:Flag of Myanmar.svg|thumb|Flag of the [[Myanmar|Republic of the Union of Myanmar]], in use since 21 October 2010.]]\n[[File:Flag of Myanmar at Byint Naung Statue Garden Park.jpg|thumb|Flag of Myanmar flown at Byint Naung Statue Garden Park in [[Kawthaung]].]]\n[[File:Flag of Myanmar and Tanintharyi Region at 1199 Mountain Peak.jpg|thumb|The flag of Myanmar flown alongside the flag of [[Tanintharyi Region]] on 1199 Mountain Peak in Kawthaung.]]\n\n[[File:Myanmar flag.jpg|thumb|Myanmar flag design]]\n\nA new design for the national flag was proposed on 10 November 2006 during a [[Constitutional convention (political meeting)|constitutional convention]].  The new flag would have consisted of three equally sized green, yellow, and red horizontal stripes, with a white star in the hoist end of the green stripe.<ref name=\"globalflag\"/>\n\nIn September 2007 another new design was proposed, this time with a larger white star in the middle and with the stripes in a different order, namely: yellow, green, red.<ref name=\"globalflag\"/> That same order was used in the flag of the [[State of Burma]] during the [[Japanese occupation of Burma]], which featured a [[green peacock]] in the centre.\n\nThe proposal was a fusion of the flag of the State of Burma without the royal peacock, taking instead the white star that symbolised the Union of Burma in the canton of its flag.\n\nThe flag proposed in September 2007 was included in the [[Constitution of Burma#2008 Constitution|new constitution]], and was accepted with the [[2008 Burmese constitutional referendum|2008 referendum]].<ref name=\"Robert Birsel\">{{cite news|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCATRE69K2HM20101021|title=Myanmar gets new flag, official name, anthem|last=Birsel|first=Robert|date=21 October 2010|work=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=23 October 2010}}</ref> Officials were told to lower the old flag in favour of the new one only shortly before 3:00&nbsp;p.m. local time on 21 October 2010.<ref name=\"st\"/> Orders were also handed out to ensure all old flags were burned.<ref name=\"Robert Birsel\" /> The adoption of the new flag was announced on state media just prior to the flag changing.<ref name=\"st\"/>\n\nThe new flag is a horizontal tricolor flag of yellow, green, and red charged with a [[five-pointed star|five-pointed]] white star in the middle of the field. The yellow represents solidarity; the green symbolizes peace, tranquility and lush greenery; the red represents courage and determination; and the white star stands for the significance of the union of the country.<ref name=\"globalflag\"/> Green, yellow, and red are also considered the [[Pan-African colours]], leading commentators to note that the new flag looked distinctly \"African\" and even that it was being confused for the flag of an African country.<ref name=Reuters1>{{cite news|last=Cropley |first=Ed |title=Myanmar's African Flag |url=http://blogs.reuters.com/africanews/2010/11/10/myanmars-african-flag/ |accessdate=8 December 2013 |newspaper=Reuters |date=10 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213010623/http://blogs.reuters.com/africanews/2010/11/10/myanmars-african-flag/ |archivedate=13 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 proposals ===\n\nThe ruling [[National League for Democracy]] (NLD) proposed a series of constitutional amendments in July 2019, including one to change the national flag. Four political parties, the NLD, [[Shan Nationalities League for Democracy|SNLD]], [[Zomi Congress for Democracy|ZCD]] and [[National Unity Party (Myanmar)|NUP]] proposed four designs of flags.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=\u1019\u103c\u1014\u103a\u1019\u102c\u1014\u102d\u102f\u1004\u103a\u1004\u1036 \u1021\u101c\u1036\u1000\u102d\u102f\u1015\u103c\u1031\u102c\u1004\u103a\u1038\u1001\u103b\u1004\u103a\u101e\u1030\u1010\u103d\u1031 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/burmese/burma-49024283|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=17 July 2019}}</ref> The NLD proposed changing the national flag as they do not believe that the flag adopted in 2010 has the full support of the people of Myanmar.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cho |first1=Phyo Thiha |title=NLD Wants Military Lawmakers Out of Parliament By 2035\u2026 And a New National Flag |url=https://www.myanmar-now.org/en/news/nld-wants-military-lawmakers-out-of-parliament-by-2035-and-a-new-national-flag |accessdate=10 December 2019 |work=Myanmar Now |date=24 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Their proposed flag was based on the flag adopted by the country at independence and consists of a red field with a blue canton in the upper hoist. Within the blue canton is a large white star representing the union which is surrounded by 14 smaller white stars representing the states and regions of the country.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thar |first1=Hein |title=NLD among four parties seeking new national flag |url=https://frontiermyanmar.net/en/nld-among-four-parties-seeking-new-national-flag |accessdate=10 December 2019 |work=Frontier Myanmar |date=24 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFlag of Myanmar (2019 proposal).svg|The NLD's proposal\nFile:Flag of Myanmar - Shan Nationalities League for Democracy (SNLD)'s proposal 2019.svg|The SNLD's proposal\nFile:Flag of Myanmar - Zomi Congress for Democracy (ZCD)'s proposal 2019.svg|The ZCD's proposal\nFile:Flag of Myanmar - The National Unity Party (NUP)'s proposal 2019.svg|The NUP's proposal\n</gallery>\n\n=== Historic flags ===\n<gallery>\nFile:Golden Hintar flag of Burma.svg|Flag used in the [[Hanthawaddy Kingdom]] (c.1300\u20131500)\nFile:Flag of the Alaungpaya Dynasty of Myanmar.svg|Flag of the Third Burmese Empire under the [[Konbaung dynasty]] (1752\u20131885)\nFile:Flag of the United Kingdom.svg|Flag of [[British Burma]] as a part of [[British India]] (1824\u20131937)\nFile:British Burma 1937 flag.svg|Flag of [[British Burma]] as a separate colony (1939\u20131941; 1945 \u2013 January 3, 1948)\nFile:Flag of Burma (1941\u20131942).svg|Provisional flag of [[British Burma]] (30 March 1941\u20131942)\nFile:Merchant flag of Japan (1870).svg|Provisional flag used during the [[Japanese occupation of Burma|Japanese Occupation]] (1942\u20131943)\nFile:Flag of the State of Burma (1943-45).svg|Flag of the [[State of Burma]] (1943\u20131945)\nFile:Flag of Burma 1943.svg|Variant design of the flag of the State of Burma (1943\u20131945)\n</gallery>\n\n== Photo gallery ==\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Heraldry}}\n* [[List of Burmese flags]]\n* [[State seal of Myanmar]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Flags of Myanmar}}\n* {{FOTW|id=mm|title=Myanmar}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120406101349/http://www.myanmars.net/myanmar/myanmar-flag-emblem.htm Timeline Flag of Myanmar]\n\n{{Burma (Myanmar) topics}}\n{{Asia topic|Flag of|title=[[Flags of Asia]]}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flag Of Burma}}\n[[Category:Flags of Myanmar| ]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Flags introduced in 2010|Myanmar]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox flag\n| Name= Myanmar\n| Image = Flag of Myanmar.svg\n| Use = 111110\n| Symbol =\n| Proportion = 2:3<ref>State Flag Law with State Peace and Development Council Law (8/2010)</ref>\n| Adoption ={{start date and age|2010|10|21|df=yes}}\n| Design = A horizontal [[triband (flag)|triband]] of yellow, green and red; charged with a large white [[five-pointed star]] at the centre.\n}}\n\nThe current '''flag of [[Myanmar]]''' (also known as Burma) was adopted on 21 October 2010 to replace the former flag in use since 1974. The new flag was introduced along with implementing changes to the country's name, which were laid out in the 2008 Constitution.\n\nThe design of the flag has three horizontal stripes of yellow, green and red with a five-pointed white star in the middle. The three colors of the stripes are meant to symbolize solidarity, [[peace]] and tranquility, and [[courage]] and decisiveness, respectively.<ref name=\"st\">{{cite news|title=Myanmar unveils new flag |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/SEAsia/Story/STIStory_593613.html |accessdate=23 October 2010 |publisher=[[Straits Times]] |newspaper=AP |date=21 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101024201904/http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/SEAsia/Story/STIStory_593613.html |archivedate=24 October 2010 }}</ref>\n\n== Colours ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Scheme !! style=\"background-color:#FECB00\"|Yellow !! style=\"background-color:#34B233\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">Green</span> !! style=\"background-color:#EA2839\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">Red</span> !! style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"|White\n|-\n| '''[[Pantone]]''' || 116 || 361 || 1788 || Safe\n|-\n| '''[[RGB color model|RGB]]''' || 254-203-0 || 52-178-51 || 234-40-57 || 255-255-255\n|-\n| '''[[Hexadecimal]]''' || #FECB00 || #34B233 || #EA2839 || #FFFFFF\n|-\n| '''[[CMYK color model|CMYK]]''' || 0, 20, 100, 0 || 76, 0, 100, 0 || 0, 98, 82, 0 || 0, 0, 0, 0\n|}\n\n== History ==\n\n=== 1948 flag ===\n[[File:Flag of Burma (1948-1974).svg|thumb|Flag of the [[Post-independence Burma, 1948\u201362|Union of Burma]] (4 January 1948 \u2013 3 January 1974).<br />Proportion 5:9; National flag and State ensign.]]\n\nThe two flags used by the country immediately prior to the 2010 flag both originated in the Burmese Resistance, which adopted a red flag with a white star when fighting the [[Japanese occupation of Burma|occupying Japanese forces]] during [[World War II]].\n\nThe flag adopted upon independence from the [[United Kingdom]] on 4 January 1948 consisted of a red field with a blue canton. The blue canton was charged with one large white star, representing the union, surrounded by 5 smaller stars representing the main ethnic groups found within the newly independent state.<ref>[http://www.myanmars.net/myanmar/myanmar-flag-emblem.htm#National_Flag Myanmar (Burma) : former flags] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406101349/http://www.myanmars.net/myanmar/myanmar-flag-emblem.htm |date=6 April 2012 }}. Myanmars.net (4 January 1948). Retrieved on 2011-05-27.</ref> This flag remained in use until January 1974 and has a ratio of 5:9.<ref>[http://www.fotw.net/flags/mm-old.html#oldflag Myanmar (Burma): former flags]. Fotw.net. Retrieved on 27 May 2011. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429004112/http://www.fotw.net/flags/mm-old.html#oldflag |date=29 April 2011 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Colours scheme !! style=\"background-color:#2042a1ff\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">Blue</span> !! style=\"background-color:#da2d1cff\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">Red</span> !! style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"|White\n|-\n| '''[[RGB color model|RGB]]'''   || 32-66-161 || 218-45-28 || 255-255-255\n|-\n| '''[[Hexadecimal]]'''  || #2042a1ff || #da2d1cff || #FFFFFF\n|-\n| '''[[CMYK color model|CMYK]]'''  || 80, 59, 0, 37 || 0, 79, 87, 15 || 0, 0, 0, 0\n|}\n\n=== 1974 flag ===\n[[File:Flag of Myanmar (1974-2010).svg|thumb|Flag of the [[Burmese Way to Socialism|Socialist Republic of the Union of Burma]] (3 January 1974 \u2013 18 September 1988) and the [[State Peace and Development Council|Union of Myanmar]] (18 September 1988 \u2013 21 October 2010).<br />\nProportion 5:9; National flag and State ensign.]]\n\nThe new flag adopted on 3 January 1974 upon the declaration of a [[socialist republic]] by [[Ne Win]] has a similar ratio as the previous flag and depicted 14 stars, encircling a gear and a rice plant (the logo of the [[Burma Socialist Programme Party]]) in a blue-coloured canton against a red field. The rice stands for agriculture, the gear represents industry, and the 14 stars represent each of the [[administrative divisions of Burma|14 member states]] of the Union.<ref name=\"globalflag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalflag.idv.tw/zy/mmr.htm|title=\u7dec\u7538 Myanmar/Burma|last=Tai|first=Yu-liang|language=Chinese|accessdate=23 October 2010}}</ref> The 14-star flag was hung upside down during the [[8888 Uprising]] of 1988 by the protesters as a sign of protest against the military government.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Colours scheme !! style=\"background-color:#2042a1ff\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">Blue</span> !! style=\"background-color:#da2d1cff\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">Red</span> !! style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"|White\n|-\n| '''[[RGB color model|RGB]]'''   || 32-66-161 || 218-45-28 || 255-255-255\n|-\n| '''[[Hexadecimal]]'''  || #2042a1ff || #da2d1cff || #FFFFFF\n|-\n| '''[[CMYK color model|CMYK]]'''  || 80, 59, 0, 37 || 0, 79, 87, 15 || 0, 0, 0, 0\n|}\n\n=== 2010 flag ===\n[[File:Flag of Myanmar.svg|thumb|Flag of the [[Myanmar|Republic of the Union of Myanmar]], in use since 21 October 2010.]]\n[[File:Flag of Myanmar at Byint Naung Statue Garden Park.jpg|thumb|Flag of Myanmar flown at Byint Naung Statue Garden Park in [[Kawthaung]].]]\n[[File:Flag of Myanmar and Tanintharyi Region at 1199 Mountain Peak.jpg|thumb|The flag of Myanmar flown alongside the flag of [[Tanintharyi Region]] on 1199 Mountain Peak in Kawthaung.]]\n\n[[File:Myanmar flag.jpg|thumb|Myanmar flag design]]\n\nA new design for the national flag was proposed on 10 November 2006 during a [[Constitutional convention (political meeting)|constitutional convention]].  The new flag would have consisted of three equally sized green, yellow, and red horizontal stripes, with a white star in the hoist end of the green stripe.<ref name=\"globalflag\"/>\n\nIn September 2007 another new design was proposed, this time with a larger white star in the middle and with the stripes in a different order, namely: yellow, green, red.<ref name=\"globalflag\"/> That same order was used in the flag of the [[State of Burma]] during the [[Japanese occupation of Burma]], which featured a [[green peacock]] in the centre.\n\nThe proposal was a fusion of the flag of the State of Burma without the royal peacock, taking instead the white star that symbolised the Union of Burma in the canton of its flag.\n\nThe flag proposed in September 2007 was included in the [[Constitution of Burma#2008 Constitution|new constitution]], and was accepted with the [[2008 Burmese constitutional referendum|2008 referendum]].<ref name=\"Robert Birsel\">{{cite news|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCATRE69K2HM20101021|title=Myanmar gets new flag, official name, anthem|last=Birsel|first=Robert|date=21 October 2010|work=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=23 October 2010}}</ref> Officials were told to lower the old flag in favour of the new one only shortly before 3:00&nbsp;p.m. local time on 21 October 2010.<ref name=\"st\"/> Orders were also handed out to ensure all old flags were burned.<ref name=\"Robert Birsel\" /> The adoption of the new flag was announced on state media just prior to the flag changing.<ref name=\"st\"/>\n\nThe new flag is a horizontal tricolor flag of yellow, green, and red charged with a [[five-pointed star|five-pointed]] white star in the middle of the field. The yellow represents solidarity; the green symbolizes peace, tranquility and lush greenery; the red represents courage and determination; and the white star stands for the significance of the union of the country.<ref name=\"globalflag\"/> Green, yellow, and red are also considered the [[Pan-African colours]], leading commentators to note that the new flag looked distinctly \"African\" and even that it was being confused for the flag of an African country.<ref name=Reuters1>{{cite news|last=Cropley |first=Ed |title=Myanmar's African Flag |url=http://blogs.reuters.com/africanews/2010/11/10/myanmars-african-flag/ |accessdate=8 December 2013 |newspaper=Reuters |date=10 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213010623/http://blogs.reuters.com/africanews/2010/11/10/myanmars-african-flag/ |archivedate=13 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 proposals ===\n\nThe ruling [[National League for Democracy]] (NLD) proposed a series of constitutional amendments in July 2019, including one to change the national flag. Four political parties, the NLD, [[Shan Nationalities League for Democracy|SNLD]], [[Zomi Congress for Democracy|ZCD]] and [[National Unity Party (Myanmar)|NUP]] proposed four designs of flags.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=\u1019\u103c\u1014\u103a\u1019\u102c\u1014\u102d\u102f\u1004\u103a\u1004\u1036 \u1021\u101c\u1036\u1000\u102d\u102f\u1015\u103c\u1031\u102c\u1004\u103a\u1038\u1001\u103b\u1004\u103a\u101e\u1030\u1010\u103d\u1031 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/burmese/burma-49024283|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=17 July 2019}}</ref> The NLD proposed changing the national flag as they do not believe that the flag adopted in 2010 has the full support of the people of Myanmar.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cho |first1=Phyo Thiha |title=NLD Wants Military Lawmakers Out of Parliament By 2035\u2026 And a New National Flag |url=https://www.myanmar-now.org/en/news/nld-wants-military-lawmakers-out-of-parliament-by-2035-and-a-new-national-flag |accessdate=10 December 2019 |work=Myanmar Now |date=24 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Their proposed flag was based on the flag adopted by the country at independence and consists of a red field with a blue canton in the upper hoist. Within the blue canton is a large white star representing the union which is surrounded by 14 smaller white stars representing the states and regions of the country.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thar |first1=Hein |title=NLD among four parties seeking new national flag |url=https://frontiermyanmar.net/en/nld-among-four-parties-seeking-new-national-flag |accessdate=10 December 2019 |work=Frontier Myanmar |date=24 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFlag of Myanmar (2019 proposal).svg|The NLD's proposal\nFile:Flag of Myanmar - Shan Nationalities League for Democracy (SNLD)'s proposal 2019.svg|The SNLD's proposal\nFile:Flag of Myanmar - Zomi Congress for Democracy (ZCD)'s proposal 2019.svg|The ZCD's proposal\nFile:Flag of Myanmar - The National Unity Party (NUP)'s proposal 2019.svg|The NUP's proposal\n</gallery>\n\n=== Historic flags ===\n<gallery>\nFile:Golden Hintar flag of Burma.svg|Flag used in the [[Hanthawaddy Kingdom]] (c.1300\u20131500)\nFile:Flag of the Alaungpaya Dynasty of Myanmar.svg|Flag of the Third Burmese Empire under the [[Konbaung dynasty]] (1752\u20131885)\nFile:Flag of the United Kingdom.svg|Flag of [[British Burma]] as a part of [[British India]] (1824\u20131937)\nFile:British Burma 1937 flag.svg|Flag of [[British Burma]] as a separate colony (1939\u20131941; 1945 \u2013 January 3, 1948)\nFile:Flag of Burma (1941\u20131942).svg|Provisional flag of [[British Burma]] (30 March 1941\u20131942)\nFile:Merchant flag of Japan (1870).svg|Provisional flag used during the [[Japanese occupation of Burma|Japanese Occupation]] (1942\u20131943)\nFile:Flag of the State of Burma (1943-45).svg|Flag of the [[State of Burma]] (1943\u20131945)\nFile:Flag of Burma 1943.svg|Variant design of the flag of the State of Burma (1943\u20131945)\n</gallery>\n\n== Photo gallery ==\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Heraldry}}\n* [[List of Burmese flags]]\n* [[State seal of Myanmar]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Flags of Myanmar}}\n* {{FOTW|id=mm|title=Myanmar}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120406101349/http://www.myanmars.net/myanmar/myanmar-flag-emblem.htm Timeline Flag of Myanmar]\n\n{{Burma (Myanmar) topics}}\n{{Asia topic|Flag of|title=[[Flags of Asia]]}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flag Of Burma}}\n[[Category:Flags of Myanmar| ]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Flags introduced in 2010|Myanmar]]\n", "name_user": "Yoknowwhatright", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I fix it)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flag_of_Myanmar"}
{"title_page": "IPhone SE (2020)", "text_new": "{{lowercase title}}\n{{Distinguish|text = the [[iPhone SE (original)|original iPhone SE]]}}\n{{Infobox mobile phone\n| name         = iPhone SE (2020)\n| codename     = \n| logo         = <!-- file name only, i.e. example.png -->\n| logosize     = <!-- include \"px\" - Uses users default image size if omitted -->\n| image        = <!-- file name only, i.e. example.png -->\n| imagesize    = <!-- include \"px\" - Uses users default image size if omitted -->\n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| brand        = [[Apple Inc.]]\n| manufacturer = \n| slogan       = <!-- Phone-specific slogan; must cite source -->\n| series       = 13th\n| modelnumber  = \n| networks     = \n| released     = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| available    = <!-- Country {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} (Retailer) -->\n| discontinued = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| unitssold    = \n| unitsshipped = \n| predecessor  = [[iPhone SE (original)|iPhone SE]]<br>[[iPhone 8]]\n| successor    =  [[iPhone 12]]\n| related = [[iPhone XR]]<br>[[iPhone 11]]<br>[[iPhone 11 Pro|iPhone 11 Pro/Pro Max]]\n| type         = \n| form         = \n| size         = <!-- {{convert|NNN|mm|in|abbr=on}} H <br /> {{convert|NNN|mm|in|abbr=on}} W <br /> {{convert|NNN|mm|in|abbr=on}} D -->\n| weight       = <!-- {{convert|NNN|g|oz|abbr=on}} -->\n| os           = [[iOS 13]] <!-- (Please change to specific number at release)Operating system at initial release, then optionally list \"upgrades to\", etc. -->\n<!-- | '''Original:''' For use ONLY after release of iOS 14 -->\n<!-- | '''Current:''' For use ONLY after release of iOS 14 -->\n| soc          = [[Apple A13 Bionic|A13 Bionic]]\n| cpu          = \n| gpu          = \n| modem        = \n| memory       = \n| storage      = \n| memory_card  = \n| battery      = \n| charging     =\n| input        = \n| display      = 4.7-inches, 5.5 inches (Plus model)\n| ext_display  = \n| rear_camera  = \n| front_camera = \n| sound        = \n| connectivity = \n| other        = \n| sar          = \n| hac          = \n| website      = <!-- {{URL|www.apple.com}} Please DO NOT add anything until the iPhone SE 2 webpage is set up! -->\n| references   = \n}}\nThe '''second-generation iPhone SE''' (colloquially referred to as the '''iPhone SE 2''' and the '''iPhone 9''') is an upcoming [[iPhone]] that will serve as the successor to both the [[iPhone SE]] and the [[iPhone 8]], and has been rumored since 2017, a year after the [[iPhone SE]] was released. It is the 13th generation of the iPhone, along with the higher-end [[iPhone 11]] and flagship [[iPhone 11 Pro|11 Pro/Pro Max]]. Although many people called it the \"iPhone SE 2\" and \"iPhone 9\", an Apple.com listing showed that it is, in fact, called the '''iPhone SE'''. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/4/2/21206497/iphone-se-9-name-4-7-inch-2020-store-leak|title=Apple Store leaks 4.7-inch \u2018iPhone SE\u2019 name|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It was scheduled to be announced on March 31, 2020,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tomsguide.com/news/iphone-9-price-and-release-date-just-confirmed|title=iPhone 9 price and release date just confirmed|last=Priday|first=Richard|website=Tom's Guide|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> but the date of announcement has been shifted to April 15, with shipments starting April 22. However, cases for this phone are already being shipped to [[Best Buy]], showing an iPhone with an [[iPhone 8]]-sized body, a single camera lens much like an [[iPhone XR]] for the regular model, and a dual-lens camera much like an [[iPhone 8 Plus]] for the Plus model, which is also the size of the aforementioned iPhone 8 Plus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9to5mac.com/2020/03/30/iphone-9-case-inventory-best-buy/|title=iPhone 9 case inventory arriving at Best Buy, other retailers with April 5 merchandising date|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Belkin]] screen protectors for this phone are also being sold at the [[Apple Store]], with a 4.7 inch height that also fits well with the regular-sized versions of the [[iPhone 8]] and [[iPhone 7]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tomsguide.com/news/apple-iphone-9-will-be-the-new-iphone-se?utm_source=notification|title=iPhone 9 is the new iPhone SE|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The SE may have already entered mass production. Although the iPhone SE cases arrived on March 31, Best Buy employees have been advised not to start selling them until April 5, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9to5mac.com/2020/03/30/iphone-9-case-inventory-best-buy/|title=iPhone 9 case inventory arriving at Best Buy, other retailers with April 5 merchandising date|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The iPhone SE will ship with [[iOS 13]] and will also support [[iOS 14]].\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n\n\n[[Category:IPhone]]\n", "text_old": "{{lowercase title}}\n{{Distinguish|text = the [[iPhone SE (original)|original iPhone SE]]}}\n{{Infobox mobile phone\n| name         = iPhone SE (2020)\n| codename     = \n| logo         = <!-- file name only, i.e. example.png -->\n| logosize     = <!-- include \"px\" - Uses users default image size if omitted -->\n| image        = <!-- file name only, i.e. example.png -->\n| imagesize    = <!-- include \"px\" - Uses users default image size if omitted -->\n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| brand        = [[Apple Inc.]]\n| manufacturer = \n| slogan       = <!-- Phone-specific slogan; must cite source -->\n| series       = 13th\n| modelnumber  = \n| networks     = \n| released     = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| available    = <!-- Country {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} (Retailer) -->\n| discontinued = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| unitssold    = \n| unitsshipped = \n| predecessor  = [[iPhone SE (original)|iPhone SE]]<br>[[iPhone 8]]\n| successor    =  [[iPhone 12]]\n| related = [[iPhone XR]]<br>[[iPhone 11]]<br>[[iPhone 11 Pro|iPhone 11 Pro/Pro Max]]\n| type         = \n| form         = \n| size         = <!-- {{convert|NNN|mm|in|abbr=on}} H <br /> {{convert|NNN|mm|in|abbr=on}} W <br /> {{convert|NNN|mm|in|abbr=on}} D -->\n| weight       = <!-- {{convert|NNN|g|oz|abbr=on}} -->\n| os           = [[iOS 13]] <!-- (Please change to specific number at release)Operating system at initial release, then optionally list \"upgrades to\", etc. -->\n<!-- | '''Original:''' For use ONLY after release of iOS 14 -->\n<!-- | '''Current:''' For use ONLY after release of iOS 14 -->\n| soc          = [[Apple A13 Bionic|A13 Bionic]]\n| cpu          = \n| gpu          = \n| modem        = \n| memory       = \n| storage      = \n| memory_card  = \n| battery      = \n| charging     =\n| input        = \n| display      = 4.7-inches, 5.5 inches (Plus model)\n| ext_display  = \n| rear_camera  = \n| front_camera = \n| sound        = \n| connectivity = \n| other        = \n| sar          = \n| hac          = \n| website      = <!-- {{URL|www.apple.com}} Please DO NOT add anything until the iPhone SE 2 webpage is set up! -->\n| references   = \n}}\nThe '''second-generation iPhone SE''' (colloquially referred to as the '''iPhone SE 2''' and the '''iPhone 9''') is an upcoming [[iPhone]] that will serve as the successor to both the [[iPhone SE]] and the [[iPhone 8]], and has been rumored since 2017, a year after the [[iPhone SE]] was released. It is the 13th generation of the iPhone, along with the higher-end [[iPhone 11]] and flagship [[iPhone 11 Pro|11 Pro/Pro Max]]. Although many people called it the \"iPhone SE 2\" and \"iPhone 9\", an Apple.com listing showed that it is, in fact, called the '''iPhone SE'''. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/4/2/21206497/iphone-se-9-name-4-7-inch-2020-store-leak|title=Apple Store leaks 4.7-inch \u2018iPhone SE\u2019 name|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It was scheduled to be announced on March 31, 2020,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tomsguide.com/news/iphone-9-price-and-release-date-just-confirmed|title=iPhone 9 price and release date just confirmed|last=Priday|first=Richard|website=Tom's Guide|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> but the date of announcement has been shifted to April 15, with shipments starting April 22. However, cases for this phone are already being shipped to [[Best Buy]], showing an iPhone with an [[iPhone 8]]-sized body, a single camera lens much like an [[iPhone XR]] for the regular model, and a dual-lens camera much like an [[iPhone 8 Plus]] for the Plus model, which is also the size of the aforementioned iPhone 8 Plus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9to5mac.com/2020/03/30/iphone-9-case-inventory-best-buy/|title=iPhone 9 case inventory arriving at Best Buy, other retailers with April 5 merchandising date|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Belkin]] screen protectors for this phone are also being sold at the [[Apple Store]], with a 4.7 inch height that also fits well with the regular-sized versions of the [[iPhone 8]] and [[iPhone 7]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tomsguide.com/news/apple-iphone-9-will-be-the-new-iphone-se?utm_source=notification|title=iPhone 9 is the new iPhone SE|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The SE may have already entered mass production. Although the iPhone SE cases arrived on March 31, Best Buy employees have been advised not to start selling them until April 5, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9to5mac.com/2020/03/30/iphone-9-case-inventory-best-buy/|title=iPhone 9 case inventory arriving at Best Buy, other retailers with April 5 merchandising date|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The iPhone SE ship with [[iOS 13]] and will also support [[iOS 14]].\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n\n\n[[Category:IPhone]]\n", "name_user": "Prahlad balaji", "label": "safe", "comment": "correcting a grammatical error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPhone_SE_(2020)"}
{"title_page": "Gas Gas", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n{{peacock|date=December 2009}}\n}}\n\n:''\"Gas Gas\" is also a song from the Croatian musician [[Severina Vu\u010dkovi\u0107|Severina]] (Album: [[Zdravo Marijo]]).''\n[[File:Gas Gas EC 300 2009.jpg|thumb|2008 GasGas EC Racing edition with full \u00d6hlins suspension]]\n\n'''Gas Gas''' is a Spanish [[motorcycle]] manufacturer established in 1985 by Narc\u00ecs Casas and Josep Pibernat in [[Salt, Girona]].<ref name=\"Gas Gas History 1985\">{{cite web |url=https://www.retrotrials.com/gas-gas-history-1985.html |title=Gas Gas History 1985 |publisher=retrotrials.com |accessdate=3 April 2020 }}</ref> The company specializes in [[off-road]] motorcycles for [[Motorcycle trials|trials]] and [[enduro]] competitions. Gas Gas was purchased by [[KTM]] motorcycles in 2019.<ref name=\"KTM Buys Gas Gas\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cyclenews.com/2019/09/article/ktm-buys-gasgas/ |title=KTM Buys Gas Gas |publisher=cyclenews.com |accessdate=29 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"KTM Buys Gas Gas Well 60 Percent of it at Least\">{{cite web |url=https://motocrossactionmag.com/ktm-buys-gas-gas-well-60-percent-of-it-at-least/ |title=KTM Buys Gas Gas Well 60 Percent of it at Least |publisher=motocrossactionmag.com |accessdate=29 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Company history==\nIn 1973, Narc\u00ecs Casas and Josep Pibernat began operating a [[Bultaco]] motorcycle franchise in Salt.<ref name=\"Gas Gas History 1985\"/> With the financial demise of the Bultaco factory in 1979, Casas and Pibernat began importing Italian [[SWM (motorcycles)|SWM]] motorcycles until 1984 when, the manufacturer ceased operations.<ref name=\"Gas Gas History 1985\"/> \n\nCasas and Pibernat then embarked on a programme to manufacture trials motorbikes for sale in their shop.<ref name=\"Gas Gas History 1985\"/> Gas Gas began manufacturing trials motorcycles in 1985, [[enduro]] and [[motocross]] motorcycles in 1989, and [[all-terrain vehicles|quads]] in 2002. The name Gas Gas literally means \"to gas it\" (to accelerate, give it the gas, turn the throttle - to go faster.) The Gas Gas founders have, at times, expressed misgivings about the chosen name inasmuch as that name causes confusion outside Spain. Others have joked that Gas Gas are so good that they had to name them twice. The slogan \"Gas Gas = Fast Fast\" was used by the US importer, GasGas North America, from 1999\u20132002 to try to help people understand the unique name.\n\nIn 2014, Gas Gas merged with the Spanish motorcycle manufacturer [[Ossa (motorcycle)|Ossa]] before being absorbed by the Torrot Group in 2015.<ref name=\"Gas Gas Motos, SA and Ossa Factory, SL join forces\">{{cite web |url=https://gasgas.com/us/news/gas-gas-motos-sa-and-ossa-factory-sl-join-forces/98/481 |title=Gas Gas Motos, SA and Ossa Factory, SL join forces |publisher=gasgas.com |accessdate=29 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"Gas Gas and Ossa Merge\">{{cite web |url=https://www.asphaltandrubber.com/news/gas-gas-ossa-merger/ |title=Gas Gas and Ossa Merge |publisher=asphaltandrubber.com |accessdate=14 May 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"Classic Motocross Iron: 1971 Ossa 250 Stiletto\">{{cite web |url=https://motocrossactionmag.com/classic-motocross-iron-1971-ossa-250-stiletto/ |title=Classic Motocross Iron: 1971 Ossa 250 Stiletto |publisher=motocrossactionmag.com |accessdate=29 March 2020 }}</ref> In 2019, Gas Gas was purchased by [[KTM]] motorcycles.<ref name=\"KTM Buys Gas Gas\"/><ref name=\"KTM Buys Gas Gas Well 60 Percent of it at Least\"/>\n\n[[File:Gg06ragatrials.jpg|thumb|2006 GasGas Raga edition trials bike]]\n\n==Championships and riders==\n[[File:Ggpaddock.jpg|left|thumb|GasGas trials paddock, Duluth, MN 2004.]]\nIn 1993, Gas Gas succeeded in luring the multiple [[List of motorcycle trials champions|world trials champion]] [[Jordi Tarr\u00e9s (motorcycle racer)|Jordi Tarr\u00e9s]] away from [[Beta (motorcycle manufacturer)|Beta]] and he promptly won three successive world trials championships (1993, 1994 and 1995) for GasGas.\n\nMore recently Gas Gas won the Trial Outdoor World Championship twice (2005 and 2006) with [[Adam Raga]]. It has also won the Trial Indoor World Championship in 2003, 2004, 2005 and 2006 also with Raga riding.<ref>[http://www.trialonline.org trialonline.org]</ref><ref>[http://www.indoortrial.com/ indoortrial.com]</ref>\n\nGas Gas has also been successful in the [[World Enduro Championship]]. [[Paul Edmondson (enduro rider)|Paul Edmondson]] won the 125 cc world championship in 1994 and the 250cc class in 1996, [[Petteri Silv\u00e1n]] the 250cc and the overall championship in 1999, and [[Petri Pohjamo]] the 125cc class in 2003.<ref>[http://we.abc-wec.com abc-wec.com]</ref>\n\nIn 2006, British Enduro Champion [[Wayne Braybrook]], riding a Gas Gas, was one of only two riders to finish all 80 miles of the [[Red Bull]] [[Last Man Standing (motorcycle race)|Last Man Standing]] event. 126 other riders did not finish the race.<ref>[http://www.redbulllastmanstanding.com/ redbulllastmanstanding.com]</ref>\n\n==Importing==\nGas Gas bikes are currently [[import]]ed into many countries in [[Europe]] and around the world, including [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[Canada]], [[South America]], [[South Africa]] and the [[United States]].<ref>[http://www.gasgasmotos.es/eng/db/dis.htm gasgasmotos.es] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080128150843/http://www.gasgasmotos.es/eng/db/dis.htm |date=2008-01-28 }}</ref>\n\n==Models==\n\n===Enduro/off-road===\n[[File:Mc250-2005.jpg|right|thumb|2005 MC 250 [[Motocross]] bike.]]\nWhile the ''EC'' (\"Endurocross\") and ''MC'' (motocross) models are shipped worldwide, GasGas has manufactured specialized models for the United States [[off-road]] market. The ''XC'' (\"Cross Country\" produced from 1999\u20132002) and the ''DE'' (\"Dealer Edition\" produced from 2002\u20132006) models were successful attempts to customize the product to the US market.\n\nThe ''FSE'' and ''FSR'' are the fuel injected, four-stroke [[enduro]] bikes similar in appearance to the ''EC'' models.\n\nPrior to 2007, each color on the ''EC'' model line represented the [[engine displacement]] range of the motor.\n* ''Yellow'' \u2013 125 cc and 200 cc.\n* ''Red'' \u2013 50 cc, 250 cc, 400 cc and 450 cc.\n* ''Blue'' \u2013 300 cc, 450 cc.\n\nIn 2007\u20132009, the company standardised to the colour red for all displacements and models. As of the 2010 model year, all standard EC models are black with red and white accents. The \"Six Days\" edition uses white plastics with red, yellow, and black accents. The \"Racing\" models are white with black and yellow accents.\n\n===Trials===\nThe ''TXT'' models are specifically designed for trials riding. The ''TXT'' trials model line also used a similar color code to the '''EC''' line.\n\n===Quads===\n[[File:Gas Gas Wild HP 240.jpg|thumb|2005 Gas Gas Wild HP240 Quad]]\nThe GasGas [[all-terrain vehicles|sport quads]] are known by the ''Wild HP'' brand and come in two-stroke and fuel injected four-stroke models.\n\nPrior to 2007, the ''Wild HP'' line of quads were available in choice of blue or red regardless of displacement. Beginning in 2007 the ''Wild HP'' line standardized to black.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:GasGas_EC200_2000.jpg|2000 Gas Gas EC 200, an [[enduro]] bike\nFile:Gas Gas XC 250.jpg|2001 Gas Gas XC 250 USA market only (XC produced from 1999-2002)\nFile:2003 Gas Gas EC 200.JPG|2003 Gas Gas EC 200 with full Ohlins suspension\nFile:Gas Gas MC 50 Boy.jpg|2003 Gas Gas EC50 Boy mini bike\nFile:Gas Gas EC 300.jpg|2004 Gas Gas DE 300 US market only\nFile:2003_Gas_Gas_EC_250.jpg|2003 Gas Gas EC 250\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Official website|http://gasgasmotos.es/en/home.html}}\n<!--========================({{No More Links}})============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA  |\n    | IS NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS 