ch 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"KTM Buys Gas Gas Well 60 Percent of it at Least\">{{cite web |url=https://motocrossactionmag.com/ktm-buys-gas-gas-well-60-percent-of-it-at-least/ |title=KTM Buys Gas Gas Well 60 Percent of it at Least |publisher=motocrossactionmag.com |accessdate=29 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Company history==\nIn 1973, Narc\u00ecs Casas and Josep Pibernat began operating a [[Bultaco]] motorcycle franchise in Salt.<ref name=\"Gas Gas History 1985\"/> With the financial demise of the Bultaco factory in 1979, Casas and Pibernat began importing Italian [[SWM (motorcycles)|SWM]] motorcycles until 1984 when, the manufacturer ceased operations.<ref name=\"Gas Gas History 1985\"/> \n\nCasas and Pibernat then embarked on a programme to manufacture trials motorbikes for sale in their shop.<ref name=\"Gas Gas History 1985\"/> Gas Gas began manufacturing trials motorcycles in 1985, [[enduro]] and [[motocross]] motorcycles in 1989, and [[all-terrain vehicles|quads]] in 2002. The name Gas Gas literally means \"to gas it\" (to accelerate, give it the gas, turn the throttle - to go faster.) The Gas Gas founders have, at times, expressed misgivings about the chosen name inasmuch as that name causes confusion outside Spain. Others have joked that Gas Gas are so good that they had to name them twice. The slogan \"Gas Gas = Fast Fast\" was used by the US importer, GasGas North America, from 1999\u20132002 to try to help people understand the unique name.\n\nIn 2014, Gas Gas merged with the Spanish motorcycle manufacturer [[Ossa (motorcycle)|Ossa]] before being absorbed by the Torrot Group in 2015.<ref name=\"Gas Gas Motos, SA and Ossa Factory, SL join forces\">{{cite web |url=https://gasgas.com/us/news/gas-gas-motos-sa-and-ossa-factory-sl-join-forces/98/481 |title=Gas Gas Motos, SA and Ossa Factory, SL join forces |publisher=gasgas.com |accessdate=29 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"Gas Gas and Ossa Merge\">{{cite web |url=https://www.asphaltandrubber.com/news/gas-gas-ossa-merger/ |title=Gas Gas and Ossa Merge |publisher=asphaltandrubber.com |accessdate=14 May 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"Classic Motocross Iron: 1971 Ossa 250 Stiletto\">{{cite web |url=https://motocrossactionmag.com/classic-motocross-iron-1971-ossa-250-stiletto/ |title=Classic Motocross Iron: 1971 Ossa 250 Stiletto |publisher=motocrossactionmag.com |accessdate=29 March 2020 }}</ref> In 2019, Gas Gas was purchased by [[KTM]] motorcycles.<ref name=\"KTM Buys Gas Gas\"/><ref name=\"KTM Buys Gas Gas Well 60 Percent of it at Least\"/>\n\n[[File:Gg06ragatrials.jpg|thumb|2006 GasGas Raga edition trials bike]]\n\n==Championships and riders==\n[[File:Ggpaddock.jpg|left|thumb|GasGas trials paddock, Duluth, MN 2004.]]\nIn 1993, Gas Gas succeeded in luring the multiple [[List of motorcycle trials champions|world trials champion]] [[Jordi Tarr\u00e9s (motorcycle racer)|Jordi Tarr\u00e9s]] away from [[Beta (motorcycle manufacturer)|Beta]] and he promptly won three successive world trials championships (1993, 1994 and 1995) for GasGas.\n\nMore recently Gas Gas won the Trial Outdoor World Championship twice (2005 and 2006) with [[Adam Raga]]. It has also won the Trial Indoor World Championship in 2003, 2004, 2005 and 2006 also with Raga riding.<ref>[http://www.trialonline.org trialonline.org]</ref><ref>[http://www.indoortrial.com/ indoortrial.com]</ref>\n\nGas Gas has also been successful in the [[World Enduro Championship]]. [[Paul Edmondson (enduro rider)|Paul Edmondson]] won the 125 cc world championship in 1994 and the 250cc class in 1996, [[Petteri Silv\u00e1n]] the 250cc and the overall championship in 1999, and [[Petri Pohjamo]] the 125cc class in 2003.<ref>[http://we.abc-wec.com abc-wec.com]</ref>\n\nIn 2006, British Enduro Champion [[Wayne Braybrook]], riding a Gas Gas, was one of only two riders to finish all 80 miles of the [[Red Bull]] [[Last Man Standing (motorcycle race)|Last Man Standing]] event. 126 other riders did not finish the race.<ref>[http://www.redbulllastmanstanding.com/ redbulllastmanstanding.com]</ref>\n\n==Importing==\nGas Gas bikes are currently [[import]]ed into many countries in [[Europe]] and around the world, including [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[Canada]], [[South America]], [[South Africa]] and the [[United States]].<ref>[http://www.gasgasmotos.es/eng/db/dis.htm gasgasmotos.es] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080128150843/http://www.gasgasmotos.es/eng/db/dis.htm |date=2008-01-28 }}</ref>\n\n==Models==\n\n===Enduro/off-road===\n[[File:Mc250-2005.jpg|right|thumb|2005 MC 250 [[Motocross]] bike.]]\nWhile the ''EC'' (\"Endurocross\") and ''MC'' (motocross) models are shipped worldwide, GasGas has manufactured specialized models for the United States [[off-road]] market. The ''XC'' (\"Cross Country\" produced from 1999\u20132002) and the ''DE'' (\"Dealer Edition\" produced from 2002\u20132006) models were successful attempts to customize the product to the US market.\n\nThe ''FSE'' and ''FSR'' are the fuel injected, four-stroke [[enduro]] bikes similar in appearance to the ''EC'' models.\n\nPrior to 2007, each color on the ''EC'' model line represented the [[engine displacement]] range of the motor.\n* ''Yellow'' \u2013 125 cc and 200 cc.\n* ''Red'' \u2013 50 cc, 250 cc, 400 cc and 450 cc.\n* ''Blue'' \u2013 300 cc, 450 cc.\n\nIn 2007\u20132009, the company standardised to the colour red for all displacements and models. As of the 2010 model year, all standard EC models are black with red and white accents. The \"Six Days\" edition uses white plastics with red, yellow, and black accents. The \"Racing\" models are white with black and yellow accents.\n\n===Trials===\nThe ''TXT'' models are specifically designed for trials riding. The ''TXT'' trials model line also used a similar color code to the '''EC''' line.\n\n===Quads===\n[[File:Gas Gas Wild HP 240.jpg|thumb|2005 Gas Gas Wild HP240 Quad]]\nThe GasGas [[all-terrain vehicles|sport quads]] are known by the ''Wild HP'' brand and come in two-stroke and fuel injected four-stroke models.\n\nPrior to 2007, the ''Wild HP'' line of quads were available in choice of blue or red regardless of displacement. Beginning in 2007 the ''Wild HP'' line standardized to black.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:GasGas_EC200_2000.jpg|2000 Gas Gas EC 200, an [[enduro]] bike\nFile:Gas Gas XC 250.jpg|2001 Gas Gas XC 250 USA market only (XC produced from 1999-2002)\nFile:2003 Gas Gas EC 200.JPG|2003 Gas Gas EC 200 with full Ohlins suspension\nFile:Gas Gas MC 50 Boy.jpg|2003 Gas Gas EC50 Boy mini bike\nFile:Gas Gas EC 300.jpg|2004 Gas Gas DE 300 US market only\nFile:2003_Gas_Gas_EC_250.jpg|2003 Gas Gas EC 250\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Official website|http://gasgasmotos.es/en/home.html}}\n<!--========================({{No More Links}})============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA  |\n    | IS NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS NOR SHOULD IT BE USED FOR ADVERTISING. |\n    |                                                                     |\n    |           Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.  |\n    |                                                                     |\n    | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or   |\n    | replacements on this article's discussion page, or submit your link |\n    | to the relevant category at the Open Directory Project (dmoz.org)   |\n    | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template.         |\n    =======================({{No More Links}})=============================-->\n\n{{Motorcycle trials manufacturers}}\n{{Automotive industry in Spain}}\n\n[[Category:Motorcycle manufacturers of Spain]]\n[[Category:Motorcycle trials]]\n[[Category:Spanish brands]]\n", "name_user": "Orsoni", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.o